<h2>Star Rating Statistics</h2>
<p>Star ratings are the first filter. Consumers eliminate businesses below their threshold before reading a single word.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" alt="Star rating expectations table showing 31 percent require 4.5 plus stars in 2026" src="/images/blog/google-reviews-star-rating-expectations.webp" /></p>
<p><strong>14. 31% of consumers require a 4.5-star minimum rating.</strong>
Source: <a href="https://www.brightlocal.com/research/local-consumer-review-survey/">BrightLocal, 2026</a>
This is up from 17% in 2025. Nearly 1 in 3 buyers will not consider anything below 4.5 stars.</p>
<p><strong>15. 68% of consumers require a 4-star minimum rating.</strong>
Source: <a href="https://www.brightlocal.com/research/local-consumer-review-survey/">BrightLocal, 2026</a>
Up from 55% in 2025. Two-thirds of buyers now filter out anything below 4 stars.</p>
<p><strong>16. 92% of consumers factor star ratings into their decision.</strong>
Source: <a href="https://www.brightlocal.com/research/local-consumer-review-survey/">BrightLocal, 2026</a>
Only 8% say star ratings do not matter. For everyone else, stars are the first screening tool.</p>
<p><strong>17. 87% of customers engage with businesses rated 3 to 4 stars.</strong>
Source: <a href="https://wiserreview.com/blog/google-review-statistics/">WiserReview, 2026</a>
Businesses below 3 stars lose the vast majority of potential customers.</p>
<p><strong>18. A 1-star increase in rating can boost revenue by 5 to 9%.</strong>
Source: <a href="https://hbr.org/2011/09/reviews-reputation-and-revenue">Harvard Business Review</a>
Each star has direct financial value. The difference between 3.5 and 4.5 stars translates to real revenue.</p>
<p><strong>19. 76% of consumers trust mixed reviews more than all 5-star reviews.</strong>
Source: <a href="https://www.brightlocal.com/research/local-consumer-review-survey/">BrightLocal, 2026</a>
Perfect scores trigger suspicion. A mix of 4 and 5-star reviews with a few 3-star reviews appears more authentic.</p>
